{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522753"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:47:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:47:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13842"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13842"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.23,0.12,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106641"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6459"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89119"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"349"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3652"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44398"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106641"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with persistent oral thrush and nail changes that have been present for eight months despite multiple courses of topical antifungal treatment. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as an accountant. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are thick white plaques on his oral mucosa and tongue. His toenails show thickening, yellowing, and separation from the nail bed (Image 1). There are also scaly, erythematous patches with satellite lesions on his feet (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["HIV infection","Diabetes mellitus","Chronic steroid use","Poor peripheral circulation","Local trauma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with persistent candidiasis affecting multiple sites, suggesting an underlying immune dysfunction. The combination of oral thrush and cutaneous manifestations that are resistant to topical therapy warrants investigation for immunodeficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHIV infection\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely underlying cause in this demographic. Persistent mucocutaneous candidiasis is a common presentation of HIV infection, particularly when resistant to standard topical therapy. The absence of other medical conditions or medications that might explain these findings makes HIV infection particularly concerning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E can predispose to candidal infections, particularly in poorly controlled cases. However, the combination of oral and cutaneous involvement would be unusual without other symptoms of uncontrolled diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic steroid use\u003C/strong\u003E can increase susceptibility to fungal infections, but this patient has no history of steroid therapy, and the pattern of involvement would be unusual for steroid-induced immunosuppression alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoor peripheral circulation\u003C/strong\u003E might contribute to toenail fungal infections but would not explain the oral thrush or the resistant nature of the infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocal trauma\u003C/strong\u003E to the feet or nails might predispose to isolated fungal infections but would not account for the widespread involvement including oral candidiasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of \u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E infection at multiple sites that is resistant to standard therapy should always prompt consideration of underlying immune dysfunction, particularly HIV infection in adults. This patient requires HIV testing and possibly further immune function investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic mucocutaneous candidiasis in adults should prompt investigation for underlying immunodeficiency.","HIV infection commonly presents with persistent candidal infections resistant to topical therapy.","The combination of oral and cutaneous candidiasis suggests systemic immune dysfunction rather than local factors."],"references":["Chronic mucocutaneous candidiasis | DermNet [Internet]. dermnetnz.org. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/chronic-mucocutaneous-candidiasis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89119"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13842"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20790"},{"type":"media","id":"20791"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20790"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/C4JGaEf5YoEk8Lhts30vhzVe4W2rfv.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/C4JGaEf5YoEk8Lhts30vhzVe4W2rfv.jpg","isProcessed":true,"